# Fluff Date: 2026-02-26 19:50:04
overview:<p>The Nexus was born from ComStar's urgent need to rebuild following the devastating Battle of Tukayyid in 3052. Despite achieving a strategic victory that halted the Clan invasion, the Com Guards suffered grievous materiel losses that demanded rapid rearmament. Precentor Martial Anastasius Focht identified the long-mothballed Skobel MechWorks facility on Terra as a viable quick-start production asset, and the resulting Nexus transformed the sluggish Jackrabbit into a fast, agile recon striker entering Com Guard service in 3055.</p><p>The Nexus saw early promise before combat operations exposed its thin armor as a critical vulnerability, a weakness that would drive continued refinement of the platform. The design's lineage continued through the Word of Blake era and into the Dark Age, with modernized variants produced for the Blessed Order and later sold commercially by the New Earth Trading Company.</p>

capabilities:<p>The Nexus represents a complete philosophical shift from its Jackrabbit predecessor. Where the Jackrabbit relied on a single autocannon for long-range fire support, the Nexus embraces an all-energy weapons loadout optimized for close-range engagements. A Blankenburg Technologies medium laser and two medium pulse lasers provide accurate, devastating firepower at short range, while two Intek small lasers serve as weapons of last resort. A McArthur anti-missile system offers some defense against missile-equipped opponents.</p><p>The Nissan 175 standard fusion engine drives the 25-ton chassis to speeds of nearly 120 kilometers per hour, a dramatic improvement over the Jackrabbit's 97 km/h. Four Rawlings 55 jump jets provide 120 meters of jumping capability, giving the Nexus the tactical flexibility its predecessor sorely lacked. The design philosophy sacrifices effective range for mobility and close-quarters lethality, relying on speed and maneuverability to control engagement distances. An integrated C3i computer enables coordinated targeting data sharing with allied units in Level II formations.</p><p>However, the Nexus carries only two tons of Krupp 200 ferro-fibrous armor, making it exceptionally fragile by light 'Mech standards. When targeted by opponents with superior range or mobility (as occurred during Operation Odysseus) the design suffers disproportionate losses, a vulnerability that would drive development of the more heavily protected Nexus II.</p>

deployment:<p>Developed for the Blessed Order's reborn Com Guards, this variant first proved its worth on Epsilon Eridani where it proved deadly against Republic of the Sphere combined-arms formations. Built around a 175-rated light fusion engine and experimental XL gyro, the -1C upgrades its protection to light ferro-fibrous armor while mounting a medium re-engineered laser, standard medium pulse lasers, and small X-pulse lasers optimized for anti-infantry work. The variant retains the anti-missile system of the original Nexus. Following the fall of Fortress Republic, the New Earth Trading Company began selling this variant widely, apparently acting as an intermediary for the Skobel facility on Caph.</p>

history:<p>The Nexus emerged directly from the Com Guards' devastating losses at Tukayyid in 3052. While ComStar had achieved a strategic victory that halted the Clan invasion corridor, the cost in men and machines was staggering. Precentor Martial Anastasius Focht needed new production capacity immediately, and the mothballed Skobel MechWorks facility on Terra (shuttered since Kerensky ordered it closed following the Amaris Civil War) represented the fastest path to new 'Mech production. In 3054, Focht ordered the plant reactivated, directing his engineers to completely rework the unloved Jackrabbit into a modern recon striker.</p><p>The redesigned Nexus entered service in 3055 and quickly showed promise. The 366th Division reported favorable results during initial deployments, and the design's speed and all-energy weapons suite made it popular among reconnaissance formations. However, the brutal fighting during Operation Odysseus in 3058 exposed critical vulnerabilities. Like the Raijin, the Nexus's thin armor and lack of long-range firepower led to abnormally high combat losses when opponents could outmaneuver or outrange it. Nexus pilots bitterly complained about having to face designs like the Mongoose, which possessed superior speed and maneuverability.</p><p>When the Word of Blake seized Terra, they inherited the Skobel plant and continued Nexus production while planning a comprehensive overhaul. The NXS1-B variant emerged around 3062 as an interim improvement, doubling armor protection and extending engagement range with extended-range lasers, effectively serving as the progenitor for the more ambitious Nexus II redesign that would follow.</p><p>The Nexus lineage took an unexpected turn during the Dark Age. The Blessed Order's revived Com Guards received the NXS1-C, a modernized striker variant that proved effective against Republic of the Sphere forces on Epsilon Eridani. Following the fall of Fortress Republic, the New Earth Trading Company began selling the NXS1-C commercially, seemingly acting as an intermediary for the Skobel facility on Caph. The design's journey from ComStar mothballs to widespread commercial availability represents a remarkable rehabilitation for a lineage that began with the despised Jackrabbit. Far beyond the Inner Sphere, the Scorpion Empire would carry the legacy further still, using recovered Word of Blake blueprints to develop the fully Clan-tech Star Python, proof that the sound engineering of the original Skobel chassis continues to find new life across the centuries.</p>

